services, and you're going to see that cryptography today is fundamental. In achieving not just one,

00:57.040 --> 01:03.040
but five really important security services that have become really important in the security

01:03.040 --> 01:09.520
industry. But before we get into that, if you look at the word cryptography itself and you break it

01:09.520 --> 01:18.960
up into its two parts, you've got cryptos and graphy, and both of those have Greek roots. In fact,

01:18.960 --> 01:27.200
if you look at the word cryptos, it translates into the word secret and graphy translates into the

01:27.200 --> 01:36.000
word writing. So cryptography is all about writing secrets, and the obvious reason why we want to

01:36.000 --> 01:43.520
turn something into a secret is to keep it confidential. So confidentiality is the main goal of

01:43.520 --> 01:48.720
cryptography, but as you will see, there are some other ones that have become really important

01:48.720 --> 01:55.920
that cryptography can help us achieve in today's environments. In fact, these are the five services

01:55.920 --> 02:03.120
that cryptography can achieve, and very effectively. The first, of course, is confidentiality. There's

02:03.120 --> 02:09.440
nothing better than cryptography to achieve confidentiality services. In fact, we've known that for

02:09.440 --> 02:15.840
thousands of years, and that's why cryptography has been used throughout history, mostly to achieve

02:15.840 --> 02:21.680
confidentiality, but in today's environments, there's nothing better than confidentiality to really

02:21.680 --> 02:29.440
achieve that goal in a really large way. Now, cryptography can also help us with integrity,

02:29.440 --> 02:36.080
and what we mean by integrity typically is this. If I send you a message, when you receive that message,

02:36.080 --> 02:42.080
you want to know that nothing happened along the way, because things could happen along the way.

02:42.080 --> 02:49.360
For example, someone can change it purposely, or errors can happen in transmission, but regardless

02:49.360 --> 02:56.080
of what caused the change, we want to be able to identify that that information has changed

02:56.080 --> 03:01.840
along the way. So that's what integrity really means from a cryptography perspective, and to make

03:01.840 --> 03:07.360
this really easy for us, and for you, from an exam perspective. What you want to do is you want to

03:07.360 --> 03:15.360
equate integrity to hashing. That's how we achieve integrity or message integrity controls in

03:15.360 --> 03:22.560
cryptography through hashing. So hashing equals integrity. Integrity equals hashing. If you connect those

03:22.560 --> 03:29.200
two, it's going to be really useful to you. Now, we have to understand what hashing is. Hashing by

03:29.200 --> 03:38.320
definition is what we call one-way encryption. As opposed to two-way encryption. Two-way encryption

03:38.320 --> 03:44.480
means we can take something and turn it into a secret, but then we can take that secret, which is

03:44.480 --> 03:50.960
usually referred to as ciphertext, and turn it back into the original plaintext. That's two-way

03:50.960 --> 03:58.240
encryption. We can encrypt and decrypt. Two-way encryption requires keys, because keys is what makes

03:58.480 --> 04:05.280
it easy to encrypt, but also what makes it easy to decrypt at the other end. That's what we call two-way

04:05.280 --> 04:13.040
encryption. Hashing, which addresses integrity, by definition is only one-way. We take our data that

04:13.040 --> 04:19.680
we're going to send, for example, and then we one-way encrypt it, and it produces something

04:19.680 --> 04:26.160
typically called a digest that can be useful in addressing whether something happens along the

04:26.160 --> 04:31.040
way. And of course, we're going to look at these methods as we go through this presentation and show

04:31.040 --> 04:37.200
you exactly how each of these are achieved by using cryptography services. But for now, just

04:37.200 --> 04:45.760
equate integrity to hashing. Hashing means we go one-way does not require keys. Now, the third

04:45.760 --> 04:51.760
service that cryptography can provide for us is what we call authenticity. And some people

04:51.840 --> 04:58.800
refer to this as proof of origin. So don't confuse it with authentication of people. That's not what

04:58.800 --> 05:06.720
this service is in regards to authenticity or proof of origin. Means that we can authenticate and

05:06.720 --> 05:13.200
know where something came from. So if I send you a message, you'll be able to prove that it actually

05:13.200 --> 05:20.800
came from me by using cryptography services. And that in today's environments may be very important.

05:20.800 --> 05:26.560
And here's a perfect example. If we want to patch our Microsoft operating systems,

05:26.560 --> 05:32.720
we want that patch to actually come from Microsoft. So we may ask Microsoft to do something related

05:32.720 --> 05:38.640
to cryptography so that when that patch comes to us, we can do something related to cryptography

05:38.640 --> 05:45.360
that it proves to us that that patch actually came from Microsoft and not some other organization

05:45.360 --> 05:52.480
pretending to be Microsoft. That's what we refer to as authenticity or proof of origin.

05:52.480 --> 06:00.000
The next service that cryptography can provide for us is non-repudiation. The key word here is the

06:00.000 --> 06:08.720
word repudiation. If you look that up in a dictionary, it means to be able to deny. So non-repudiation

06:08.720 --> 06:15.520
means the inability to deny. You cannot deny having done something. So if I send you a message,

06:16.320 --> 06:23.040
I cannot say later that it wasn't me that sent that particular message. That's what we call

06:23.040 --> 06:29.520
non-repudiation. And very effectively, we can achieve this in cryptography. And what you want to

06:29.520 --> 06:36.480
do here, just like we equated integrity to hashing. Hashing equals integrity, integrity equals

06:36.480 --> 06:42.640
hashing. We can do the same thing here to make it easy for you. We can equate non-repudiation

06:42.640 --> 06:49.440
to digital signatures. So non-repudiation equals digital signatures, digital signatures equals

06:49.440 --> 06:56.560
non-repudiation because that's how we achieve this service called non-repudiation. Now what you

06:56.560 --> 07:02.800
also need to remember here is that there are two flavors of non-repudiation. And these are the

07:02.800 --> 07:08.800
correct terms that we need to use because they are the correct terminology used in the industry.

07:08.800 --> 07:17.760
There is non-repudiation of origin, origin, which means the sender, me as the sender, cannot say that

07:17.760 --> 07:24.560
it wasn't me that sent a particular message. You'll be able to prove it. That's non-repudiation

07:24.560 --> 07:31.920
of origin. The sender cannot deny having sent or done something. There's also non-repudiation of

07:31.920 --> 07:39.600
delivery. Delivery means you as the receiver of a message cannot say that you've received a

07:39.600 --> 07:46.240
different message than the one that you actually did receive. So that's non-repudiation of delivery

07:46.240 --> 07:52.080
and both as you'll see later are achieved through digital signatures because that's how we

07:52.080 --> 07:58.960
achieve non-repudiation. And the last service that cryptography can provide for us is a form of

07:58.960 --> 08:05.200
access control. Now you know what access control means means allowing people to access certain

08:05.200 --> 08:12.480
resources. You're authorizing people to be able to access certain resources. And here's how cryptography

08:12.480 --> 08:19.920
can achieve that. I can encrypt a file or some asset and then give you the key or some people the

08:19.920 --> 08:26.160
key to be able to decrypt it, which means I'm authorizing those individuals to be able to access

08:26.160 --> 08:32.640
that file or that resource. So that's a form of access control. And of course you need to remember

08:32.640 --> 08:38.720
these five services or memorize them because they are the five services that can be achieved

08:38.720 --> 08:46.640
